"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field depth estimation fails on Non-Lambertian materials due to violated view-consistency assumptions, while deep learning alternatives suffer from high computational costs and poor physical interpretability. By analogizing angular sampling to MRI k-space, this paper introduces a lightweight, physics-driven angular frequency-domain parsing framework that accurately classifies materials and guides adaptive depth estimation with O(HW) complexity.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with the \"Achilles' heel\" of light field 3D reconstruction: the catastrophic failure of traditional view-consistency assumptions in real-world mixed scenes containing specular and scattering materials. Immediately contrast this physical limitation with the heavy computational burden and \"black-box\" nature of current deep learning workarounds, setting the stage for a physics-based, lightweight alternative.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Conclude the related work by highlighting the fundamental dichotomy between physically interpretable but rigid Lambertian models and flexible but computationally expensive deep neural networks. Use this gap to justify the necessity of our approach: a unified, training-free physical framework that leverages inherent optical frequency properties to achieve both high interpretability and real-time efficiency.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Explain that the 2D-DFT on the 9x9 angular matrix and the dual-mask mechanism are directly motivated by the distinct spectral energy signatures of different reflection types (low-frequency for diffuse, high-frequency for specular). This physics-first design allows the model to bypass heavy training and directly extract material weights at O(HW) complexity, which subsequently dictates the component-aware depth estimation strategy.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Structure the experiments to explicitly measure the three pillars of the motivation: material classification accuracy (validating the frequency-domain parsing), depth error reduction in Non-Lambertian regions (validating the adaptive strategy), and inference speed (validating the O(HW) lightweight claim). Include ablation studies to prove that the MRI-like angular frequency features are the exact source of performance gains over baseline Lambertian or heavy CNN methods.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that the proposed MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis successfully breaks the long-standing reliance on pure Lambertian assumptions and heavy deep learning in light field processing. Emphasize that this work establishes a new, computationally minimal, and physically interpretable paradigm for robust 3D reconstruction in complex, real-world mixed-material scenes."